SIMPLE: reconcile
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Reconcile
<hw>Rec"on*cile`</hw> <pr>(-s?l`)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Reconciled</conjf>
<pr>(-s?ld`)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Reconciling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧concilier</ets>, L. <ets>reconciliare</ets>; pref.
<ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>conciliare</ets> to bring together, to unite.
See <er>Conciliate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause to be friendly
again; to conciliate anew; to restore to friendship; to bring back to
harmony; to cause to be no longer at variance; <as>as, to
<ex>reconcile</ex> persons who have quarreled</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Propitious now and <qex>reconciled</qex> by prayer.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The church [if defiled] is interdicted till it be
<qex>reconciled</qex> [i.e., restored to sanctity] by the bishop.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We pray you . . . be ye <qex>reconciled</qex> to God.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Cor. v. 20.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring to acquiescence, content, or quiet
submission; <as>as, to <ex>reconcile</ex> one's self to
afflictions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make consistent or congruous; to bring to
agreement or suitableness; -- followed by <xex>with</xex> or
<xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The great men among the ancients understood how to
<qex>reconcile</qex> manual labor with affairs of state.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some figures monstrous and misshaped appear,⟦br⟧
Considered singly, or beheld too near;⟦br⟧
Which, but proportioned to their light or place,⟦br⟧
Due distance <qex>reconciles</qex> to form and grace.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To adjust; to settle; <as>as, to <ex>reconcile</ex>
differences</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reunite; conciliate; placate; propitiate;
pacify; appease.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reconcile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Reconcile
<hw>Rec"on*cile`</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become reconciled.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Reconcilement</ent>⟦br⟧
